  <article xml:id="samplewks" label="4000">
    <title>MATH 142 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>
     For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
    </p>
    </introduction>
<!--START TYPING CONTENT FOR SESSION BELOW HERE-->
<worksheet>
    <title> Session #4 (Sections 2.3 and 2.4)</title><!-- SECTION 1-->
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
      <!--'&' and '<' are exceptional characters and are instead authored as &lt; and &amp;. See 4.1.4.2-->
    </p>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>
    <exercise><!-- #1 --> <!-- controlling workspace length is the best way to force page breaks on a worksheet -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          The introductory derivative rules are given below. For each rule, fill in the blank.
          <p>
            Derivative of a Constant: For any real number <m>k</m>, <m>\displaystyle{\frac{d}{dx}\left(k\right)=_{\rule{1.25in}{0.05mm}}}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            Derivative of a Power Function: For any real number <m>n</m>, <m>\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\left(x^{n}\right)=_{\rule{1.25in}{0.05mm}}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            Derivative of an Exponential Function: For any real number <m>b>0</m>, <m>\displaystyle{\frac{d}{dx}\left(b^x\right)=_{\rule{1.25in}{0.05mm}}}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            Derivative of a Logarithmic Function: For any real number <m>b>0</m>, <m>\displaystyle{\frac{d}{dx}\left(\log_b(x)\right)=_{\rule{1.25in}{0.05mm}}}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            Derivative of the Sum of Two Differentiable Functions: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{d}{dx}\left(f(x) + g(x)\right)=_{\rule{2in}{0.05mm}}}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            Derivative of the Difference of Two Differentiable Functions: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{d}{dx}\left(f(x) - g(x)\right)=_{\rule{2in}{0.05mm}}}</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            Derivative of a Constant Multiple of a Differentiable Function: For any real number <m>k</m>, <m>\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\left(k\cdot f(x)\right)=_{\rule{2in}{0.05mm}}</m>
          </p>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- #2 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
         The following are circumstances for which a function <m>f</m> would not be differentiable at <m>x = a</m>.
         Draw at least one example of each.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Corner or cusp
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Discontinuity
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Vertical tangent line
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    </paragraphs>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>
    <exercise number="1"><!-- #1 --><!-- must restart numbering manually for each section -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
         Suppose we want to find the instantaneous rate of change of <m>\D f(x) = 3x^{2} - x</m> using the limit definition of the derivative.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
           Write the formula for <m>f'(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="4in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>f'(x)</m> using the formula from part (a).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>f'(2)</m> using your answer from part(b).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="2"><!-- #2 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Consider <m>f(x) = \sqrt{x}.</m>
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
           Find <m>f'(x)</m> using the limit definition of the derivative.<em>Hint: Multiply by the conjugate.</em>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find <m>f'(x)</m> using the Power Rule for derivatives and verify that your answer is the same as in part (a).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  
  
    <exercise number="3"><!-- #3 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> for each of the following using introductory derivative rules. It would help to refer to the Warm up.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>y = 3x^{2}</m> 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>y = 27x+ 5</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>y = e^{-5}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>y = 8^{x}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>y = \log_{2}(x) + 2e^{x}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>y = \ln(x) + 2x^{-5}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise workspace="1in" number="4"><!-- #4 -->
      <statement><!-- #4 -->
        <p> Given <m>\displaystyle f(x)=2x^{3}+3e^{x}-5x^{-2}</m> find <m>\displaystyle f'(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  
  
    <exercise number="5"><!-- #5 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>\displaystyle \frac{d}{dt}\bigg(\sqrt[3]{t^{2}}+5 \log_{2}(t)-\frac{7}{t^{4/3}}\bigg)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  
  
    <exercise number="6"><!-- #6 -->
      <statement>
        <p> 
         Find <m>\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigg( \frac{4}{x^{5}}+4^{x}\bigg)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="7"><!-- #7 -->
      <statement>
        <p> 
          Find <m>\D \frac{d}{dx}\bigg(\frac{5x^{4}-6x^{-3}+9}{x^{2}}\bigg)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="8"><!-- #8 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Given <m>f(x) =7x^{\frac{1}{2}}-x+e</m> and <m>g(x) = \ln(x) - \frac{1}{x}</m>, find the following;
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>f'(x)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>g'(x)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>h'(x)</m> where <m>h(x) = f(x) + g(x)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>h'(1)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise number="9"><!-- #9 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use <m>\displaystyle f(x)=\frac{1}{3x^{-3}}+\frac{x^{2}}{2}-4x</m> to answer the questions below. Leave all answers in exact form (i.e., fractions, logarithmic, etc.).
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find <m>f'(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the slope of the line tangent to the graph of <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x = 1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the values of <m>x</m> where the slope of the line tangent to the graph of <m>f(x)</m> is <m>2</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the equation of the line tangent to the graph of <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x=-4</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number ="10"><!-- #10 -->
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given <m>\D h(x)=\frac{1}{3}x^{3}+6\ln(x)</m> and graph of <m>f(x)</m> below, find <m>\D g\; '(-6)</m> given <m>\D g(x)=2h(x)+f(x)+x^{3}+0.5</m>.
        </p>
        <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session4_Fig1.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription> Graph of a function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
          <description>
            <p>
              Graph of a piecewise function <m>h(x)</m> plotted on coordinate axes.
              Starting from the left, the graph begins as a straight, horizontal line from what appears to be the point <m>(-12, 5)</m> to <m>(-7, 5)</m>.
              The graph is then linear and decreases from <m>(-7, 5)</m> to <m>(-5, 1)</m>.
              The graph is then linear and increases from <m>(-5, 1)</m> to <m>(-2, 4)</m>.
              The graph is then a straight, horizontal line from <m>(-2, 4)</m> until it leaves the graph around <m>(5,4)</m>.
            </p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="11"><!-- #11 -->
     <statement>
      <p>
        Match the correct sentence to the correct formula.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths ="82% 18%" valign ="middle">
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The exact cost of making the <m>n^{th}</m> item is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The exact revenue of making the <m>n^{th}</m> item is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The exact profit of making the <m>n^{th}</m> item is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The approximate cost of making the <m>n^{th}</m> item is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The approximate revenue of making the <m>n^{th}</m> item is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The approximate profit of making the <m>n^{th}</m> item is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        <ul marker="">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\D P\; '(n-1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>P(n)-P(n-1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
             <m>\D C\; '(n-1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
             <m>C(n)-C(n-1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
             <m>R\;'(n-1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\D R(n)-R(n-1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </sidebyside>
     </statement> 
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="12"><!-- #12 -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
          The price-demand function, <m>\D p(x)</m>, and cost function, <m>\D C(x)</m>, for the production of electric saws are given by 
          <m>\D p(x)=750-0.05x^{2}</m> and <m>\D C(x)=5800+35x</m> where <m>x</m> is the number of electric saws that are sold at a price of <m>p(x)</m> 
          dollars per saw, and <m>C(x)</m> is the cost, in dollars, of producing <m>x</m> electric saws.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the revenue and profit functions. <em>Hint: <m>R(x) = x \cdot p(x)</m> </em>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The the approximate profit of making and selling the 65<m>^{th}</m> saw. Round to the nearest cent if necessary.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
           Find the exact profit of making and selling the 65<m>^{th}</m> saw. Round to the nearest cent if necessary. 
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  
  </paragraphs>
  
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Now Grades Go Up</title>
      </paragraphs>
 <exercise number="1"><!-- #1 -->
  <statement>
    <p>
      At which <m>x</m>-value(s) does <m>f(x) = x^{2} +6x-7</m> have a horizontal tangent line?
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p> <m>x = -3</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>x = -7</m> and <m>x=1</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>x = 7</m> and <m>x = -1</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>x = 6</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p> Graph of <m>f</m> has no horizontal tangent lines </p> </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
 </exercise>
 <exercise number="2"><!-- #2 -->
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the following graph of <m>p(x)</m>.
      <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session3_Fig6.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription> Graph of a function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
          <description>
            <p>
              Graph of a piecewise function <m>p(x)</m> plotted on coordinate axes.
              Starting from the bottom left, the graph increases to the point <m>(4,18.34)</m> where it is very steep and almost appears vertical around <m>x=-6</m>.
              The graph is then linear and decreases from <m>(4,18.34)</m> to <m>(8,2.34)</m>.
              The graph then picks up again at <m>(8,10.25)</m> where it increases and approaches, but doesn't touch, the vertical asymptote <m>x=10</m> until it
              leaves the coordinate axes. 
              The graph then decreases coming from the right side of the vertical asymptote and approaches, but doesn't touch, the horizontal asymptote <m>y=10</m>
              until it leaves the coordinate axes.
            </p>
          </description>
    </image>
      For which <m>x</m>-values is <m>p(x)</m> nondifferentiable?
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p> <m>x=4</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>x=8,10</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>x=-6,4</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>x=2,8,10</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p> <m>x=-6,2,4,8,10</m> </p> </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
 </exercise>

</worksheet>

  </article>

